column10:
Far Cry 5 is an open-world first-person action-adventure shooter set in fictional Hope County, Montana. It's a nice game with fun gameplay and lots of content, but don't expect a masterpiece and don't take the story too seriously. If you don't suffer from Far Cry fatigue and like repetition, give it a try.

Pros:
- Awesome visuals;
- Responsive controls;
- Good optimisation;
- Cool buddy system;
- Co-op;
- Great soundtrack;
- Decent arsenal;
- Satisfying gunplay;
- Interesting characters;
- Arcade mode;
- Fun exploration;
- Decent AI;
- Good environmental storytelling;
- Great voice acting;

Cons:
- Microtransactions;
- Boring progression system;
- Ubisoft Connect(Upaly) is a complete ass;
- Most side missions are boring;
- Gameplay loop can get very repetitive;

[h1]Predictably Disappointing[/h1]

Good gameplay buried under the usual Triple-A incompetence, lack of passion, and overprice. Get it at a 90% discount.

[b]Pros:[/b]
[list]
[*]Good shooter;

[*]Well done gospel songs for the cult;

[*]The setting creates a nice warzone experience.
[/list]

[b]Cons:[/b]
[list]
[*]Microstutters whenever the game autosaves, which is basically every time you get any item, discover any map points, or complete any activity;

[*]Broken mission scripts, softlocking game progression. In 46 hours of playtime, I had to start it from scratch 3 times, and so I gave up a third of the way through it;

[*]Poorly coded AI, getting stuck on trees, cars, and buildings instead of flanking the player. That makes so objectives like "eliminate all enemies in the area" turn into 10-minute-long hunts for every enemy who is unresponsive in the region;

[*]Minimal player progression: there are weapons and perks to be unlocked, but you get perk points so fast and easily that you max out all essential perks in a matter of 2 hours, and then for weapons there's not much difference between them, you will eventually stick to one "good enough" gun and never change your playstyle. It gets monotonous pretty quick;

[*]Lack of movement fluidity. If you fall from more than 1,5 meter, you lose health. Can't shoot while sliding on the ground. Knife throws are slow. All that makes so the best strategy is to just crouch near protections, aim above them, and click when there are heads in your crosshairs. Which would've been fine, if not for all the other problems listed above.
[/list]
